  "name": "Seven Rays — Bailey Expressions",
  "description": "The seven rays as a psychological and civilizational typology, based on Alice Bailey's system of higher and lower expressions. Where the Ancient Roots grammar looks upward (rays descending through planes of existence), this grammar looks outward: how do the rays show up in human personality, in institutions, in the rise and fall of civilizations? Each ray has a type (who you are when it dominates), a higher expression (the ray awakened), a lower expression (the ray asleep), a shadow (the ray distorted), and a planetary lord.\n\nThis is the Bailey lens — one perspective in the Seven Rays grammar family. It should be read alongside the Ancient Roots grammar, not as a replacement for it. Bailey's system is powerful and practical but carries the limitations of its early 20th-century, Western esoteric context. The typology works best as a mirror for self-recognition, not as a box to put people in.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Portraits of the seven planetary gods from Renaissance and Baroque art: Botticelli's Venus, Caravaggio's Jupiter, Velázquez's Mars. Alchemical engravings of the seven metals and their planetary correspondences from Michael Maier's Atalanta Fugiens (1617). William Blake's visionary figures. Art Nouveau illustrations of personality types. NASA planetary photographs (public domain).",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
